software.leonov.cells.optional

Class Cells

  • java.lang.Object
    • software.leonov.cells.optional.Cells

  • public final class Cells
extends Object
    Static methods for working with Cells.

    Some methods in this class are specifically documented as being null safe. Which means they will return null values (unless otherwise stated) instead of throwing NullPointerExceptions when given null arguments. All other methods should be expected to throw Exceptions in the presence of null inputs.

    Author:
    Zhenya Leonov

      • parseBoolean

        public static Optional<Boolean> parseBoolean(org.apache.poi.ss.usermodel.Cell cell)
        Returns the value of the specified cell parsed as a Boolean or an empty Optional if the cell is null or does not contain a value.

        This method is null safe.

        Note: This method defines a boolean value differently than Java. If the formatted cell value is not equal to the string "true" or "false" (ignoring case and whitespace) this call will result in an exception.

        Parameters:
        cell - the specified cell
        Returns:
        the value of the specified cell parsed as a Boolean or an empty Optional if the cell is null or does not contain a value
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the value of the cell cannot be parsed as a boolean

      • formatValue

        public static Optional<String> formatValue(org.apache.poi.ss.usermodel.Cell cell)
        Returns the formatted value of the specified cell. This method makes a best effort attempt to parse the format pattern from the specified cell. If the format cannot be parsed the default format will be used.

        This method is null safe. If the specified cell is null or blank this method will return an empty Optional. Leading and trailing whitespace is trimmed.

        The intention is to retrieve the data the exact way you would see it in Microsoft Excel, regardless of the cell type (e.g. 5.200 would be returned as 5.200 not 5.2).

        Note: This method is not equivalent to Cell.getStringCellValue().

        Parameters:
        cell - the specified cell
        Returns:
        the formatted value of the specified cell

      • setValue

        public static org.apache.poi.ss.usermodel.Cell setValue(org.apache.poi.ss.usermodel.Cell cell,
                                                        Object value)
        Sets a value for the specified cell.

        This method is not null safe. If value is null a NullPointerException will be thrown.

        If value is a Number the cell value will be set to the double value of the number by first calling Number.doubleValue() followed by Cell.setCellValue(double).

        If value is a Boolean, Calendar, Date, LocalDateTime, or RichTextString the cell value will be set by calling Cell.setCellValue(boolean), Cell.setCellValue(Calendar), Cell.setCellValue(Date), Cell.setCellValue(LocalDateTime), or Cell.setCellValue(RichTextString) respectively.

        For all other types the cell will be set to value.toString(). Note if the result of value.toString() is empty or composed exclusively of whitespace characters according to CharMatcher#WHITESPACE, it will be ignored (to insert such a string use Cell.setCellValue(String) directly).

        Parameters:
        cell - the specified cell
        value - the value to set
        Returns:
        the specified cell
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the value to set is a string which exceeds 32767 characters
